Introduction to Regression Analysis for Predictive Modelling

Regression analysis is a predictive modelling technique used to estimate and/or determine the relationship between response (dependent) variable(s) and explanatory (independent) varible(s).

What are some of the types of regression techniques?

Types Of Regression Techniques

These regression techniques are mostly driven by three metrics

  1. Number of independent variables,
  2. Type of dependent variables and
  3. Shape of regression line

For more information on the metrics

Importance of Regression analysis

Regression analysis determines significant relationship between the variables (identifies most significant variables in case of multiple explanatory variables), and it can be used as a predictive tool.

Linear Regression Modelling

A linear model

\[Y=\beta_0 + \beta_i X_i + \xi_i,\] where \(Y\) is the response variable, \(X_i\) is the explanatory variable(s). The parameters: \(\beta_0\) represents the intercept, \(\beta_i\) represents the slope of the variable(s), \(\xi_i\) represents the error term accounting for

Checking assumptions for using linear regression model using data

This is a simple example illustrating linear regression using cars data. The data set has observations recorded on the speed of cars and the distances taken to stop the cars.

Goal

  1. To build a regression model that can be used to predict distance by establishing a statistically significant linear relationship with speed.
  1. Investigate various assumptions made before choosing a linear regression model.

Before choosing a regression technique, perform explorative statistics to better understand the data. This will help you to choose the best regression technique.

head(cars) #prints 5 rows of the data
##   speed dist
## 1     4    2
## 2     4   10
## 3     7    4
## 4     7   22
## 5     8   16
## 6     9   10
dim(cars) # prints number of rows and columns of the data

Assumptions

  1. The regression model is linear in parameters (Y and X have a linear relationship). A scatter plot can be used to visualize the linear relationship between the response and explanatory variable.

A plot showing the linear relationship using ggplot

ggplot(cars, aes(speed, dist))+geom_point() #scatter plot

If the explanatory variables are >1 then a smooth scatter plot for each one of them is drawn. This might not be viable for some datasets

  1. Outliers can affect the prediction as they can easily the direction of the line of best fit. Boxplots, histograms and Tukey’s method can be used to detect outliers
ggplot(cars)+geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(speed, dist),stat = 'boxplot', outlier.color='red') #boxlot
## Warning: Continuous x aesthetic -- did you forget aes(group=...)?

The boxplot groups everything together (it even gives an error message), we can improve the plot using cut_width()

ggplot(cars,aes(speed, dist))+geom_boxplot(aes(group = cut_width(speed, 2.5)), outlier.color='red')

  1. The X variable(s) is/are normally distributed, a –density plot– can be used to see the distribution of the explanatory variable(s).
plot(density(cars$dist), main="Distance Density Plot ", ylab="Frequency", sub=paste("Skewness:", round(e1071::skewness(cars$dist), 2)))  # density plot for 'dist'
polygon(density(cars$dist)) #plot density polygon

  1. Correlation determines the level of linear dependence between the variables
cor(cars$speed, cars$dist)
## [1] 0.8068949

Distance and speed are highly correlated (positively), an increase in speed increases the distance the car has to cover before it stops.

The strong positive correltation does not imply causation, it only indicates if there is a mutual relationship, causal or not, exists between speed and distance.

After checking some of the assumptions, let us now build the model

Let’s build the model

 Model.lm<-lm(dist ~ speed, data = cars) #y~x 
summary(Model.lm)

## F-statistic: 89.57 on 1 and 48 DF,  p-value: 1.49e-12

The model is \[dist=-17.58 + 3.93 speed\]

Approximately 65% of variation in distance can be explained by speed.

What is the difference between R-squared and adjusted R-squared ?

  1. The mean of residuals is always zero or approximately zero and the mean is always zero if the sum od residuals is zero
mean(Model.lm$residuals)
## [1] 2.220446e-16
  1. Homoscedasticity of residuals / equal variance. The first plot should be fairly straight
var(cars$speed)
## [1] 27.95918
par(mfrow=c(2,2)) #splitting plotting area into 2 rows and columns
plot(Model.lm) #diagnostic plots

Linearity >> Residual vs Fitted plot: The red line should be fairly straight. If variance was not constant then the points would have been crowded with no patterns.

Homoscedasticity >> Residual vs Fitted plot: If it does not exist, the plot will exhibit a funnelshape-like pattern. The variability in X variable is positive, the X values are not the same (nearly the same).

Normality >> Q-Q plot: The residuals are normally distributed >> Y and X are normally distributed. The points fall on the normal line.

Multivariate regression

Multiple regression suffers from multicollinearity, autocorrelation, heteroskedasticity. Example data set - Boston housing data

Boston housing data Description

1. CRIM      per capita crime rate by town
2. ZN        proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 
             25,000 sq.ft.
3. INDUS     proportion of non-retail business acres per town
4. CHAS      Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds 
             river; 0 otherwise)
5. NOX       nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
6. RM        average number of rooms per dwelling
7. AGE       proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
8. DIS       weighted distances to five Boston employment centres
9. RAD       index of accessibility to radial highways
10. TAX      full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
11. PTRATIO  pupil-teacher ratio by town
12. B        1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks 
             by town
13. LSTAT    % lower status of the population
14. MEDV     Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000's

What is our response variable?

Predictive modelling. We build regression models to help us predict outcomes.

index.no.rows<-sample(1:nrow(house.data), 0.8*nrow(house.data)) #sample row indices from data
train.Data <- house.data[index.no.rows, ]  #training data
test.Data<- house.data[-index.no.rows, ] #testing data
House.Model<- lm(MEDV ~ LSTAT+PTRATIO, data = train.Data)#build model
Predict.Model<- predict(House.Model, test.Data)#predict 
Predicted.Values<- data.frame(cbind(Actual=test.Data$MEDV, Predicted=Predict.Model))#check for accuracy
head(Predicted.Values) #
##    Actual Predicted
## 6    28.7  28.42392
## 8    27.1  20.72039
## 9    16.5  11.89972
## 11   15.0  19.65667
## 18   17.5  18.25007
## 50   19.4  20.27777
cor(Predicted.Values)#confusion matrix
##              Actual Predicted
## Actual    1.0000000 0.7889418
## Predicted 0.7889418 1.0000000

Summary

Important assumptions to note

  1. The X and Y varible(s) have a linear-additive relationship
  2. The error terms must be normally distributed >> X and Y variables are
  3. The mean of the error terms are zero or approximately zero
  4. The X variables or errors are not correlated.
  5. Homoscedasticity, that is, the variation of the observations around the regressions line are constant (error terms must have constant variance)

Possible solutions

  1. For non-linearity: transform the explanatory variables such as \(log(X)\), \(\sqrt(Y)\), \(Y^2\)
  1. For heteroscedasticity: transform the response variables such as \(log(Y)\), \(\sqrt(Y)\)

If the Y variable is numeric that is, continuous or discrete fit a linear regression model (regression line is linear), else if the Y variable binary fit a logistic regression model (does not require linear relationship between X and Y variables), else if the best fit line is a curve fit a ploynomial regression model

All models are wrong, but some are useful – George Box

Most models are wrong but useful I.M.A
